TY  - JOUR
T1  - On Terminating Stochastic Games
AU  - Mine, H.
AU  - Yamada, K.
AU  - Osaki, S.
Y1  - 1970/05/01
PY  - 1970
DA  - 1970/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.16.9.560
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.16.9.560
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 560
EP  - 571
VL  - 16
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper describes a stochastic game in which the play terminates in a finite number of steps with probability 1. The game is called a terminating stochastic game. When the play terminates at any step, the play is regarded to reach to an absorbing state in the Markov chain under consideration. Hence, the terminating stochastic game is a nonstationary Markov chain with rewards in which our concern is the transient behavior before absorption. In particular, when one of the players is a dummy, the stochastic game reduces to a Markovian decision process of special type. This paper discusses such games. We introduce a new concept of rewards and formulate three problems arising in the games by linear programming. Finally, numerical examples are presented.
AB  - This paper describes a stochastic game in which the play terminates in a finite number of steps with probability 1. The game is called a terminating stochastic game. When the play terminates at any step, the play is regarded to reach to an absorbing state in the Markov chain under consideration. Hence, the terminating stochastic game is a nonstationary Markov chain with rewards in which our concern is the transient behavior before absorption. In particular, when one of the players is a dummy, the stochastic game reduces to a Markovian decision process of special type. This paper discusses such games. We introduce a new concept of rewards and formulate three problems arising in the games by linear programming. Finally, numerical examples are presented.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.16.9.560
