TY  - JOUR
T1  - Mixed Model Line Balancing with Smoothed Station Assignments
AU  - Thomopoulos, Nick T.
Y1  - 1970/05/01
PY  - 1970
DA  - 1970/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.16.9.593
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.16.9.593
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 593
EP  - 603
VL  - 16
IS  - 9
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The general practice in mixed model assembly line balancing is to assign work to stations in a manner that each station has an equal amount of work on a daily or shift basis. This paper shows how a modification to mixed model line balancing algorithms can be used so that the stations are loaded more consistently on a model by model basis as well. In addition, the modification now allows mixed model line balancing to become a plausible tool for batched assembly line processes. The procedure is general in nature and is applicable to most line balancing algorithms.
AB  - The general practice in mixed model assembly line balancing is to assign work to stations in a manner that each station has an equal amount of work on a daily or shift basis. This paper shows how a modification to mixed model line balancing algorithms can be used so that the stations are loaded more consistently on a model by model basis as well. In addition, the modification now allows mixed model line balancing to become a plausible tool for batched assembly line processes. The procedure is general in nature and is applicable to most line balancing algorithms.
